India’s Sensex Drops Tracking Asian Peers, Pares Weekly Gain

-- B y   S h i k h a r   B a l w a n i
-- 
2011-06-03T10:09:54Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-03/india-s-sensex-gains-as-foreign-funds-turn-net-buyers-of-stocks.html
India’s benchmark stock index fell,
paring its first weekly gain in three, as Asian markets slid
amid signs economic recovery in the U.S. is faltering.  Tata Motors Ltd. (TTMT) , the nation’s biggest truck maker, lost
2.3 percent and Housing Development Finance Corp., the largest
mortgage-lender, retreated 3.1 percent.  Asia ’s benchmark stock
index is headed for its longest run of weekly losses since the
collapse of Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc., after a government
report showed yesterday that more Americans than forecast filed
for  unemployment benefits  last week.  Reliance Communications
Ltd. (RCOM) , India’s second-largest cell-phone operator, led other
Reliance ADA Group companies controlled by Anil Ambani higher
after a court rejected pleas by public interest litigators
seeking to probe the billionaire.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, fell
108.74, or 0.6 percent, to 18,385.44, according to preliminary
closing prices as of 3:30 p.m. in Mumbai, paring the weekly gain
to 0.7 percent. The S&P CNX Nifty Index on the National Stock
Exchange of  India  Ltd. declined 0.5 percent to 5,525.05. Its
June futures traded at 5,533.80. The BSE 200 Index slid 0.6
percent to 2,282.67.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shikhar Balwani in Mumbai at 
 sbalwani@bloomberg.net ;  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 